1.1 Home105 As An Example¶

First try in analyzing the routine¶

The sensors recorded the real-time power, which meant normally the power of appliances was still at 0 or fluctuated slightly around a small number, but once the user started to use, the number soared immediately. What I want to do is to sort out the "soar" process to get the time period.

I didn't use the same method as what i used in kettle part. The reason I didn't have two rows minus line by line was because the fridge actually kept on working to keep food fresh and that was why the power stayed at 200w so often. I was not sure if user really opened the fridge when the power shows 300w or 400w. However, when the power numbers went to 1000w or above, I was definitely sure the user was open the fridge. Or, the power of a fridge couldn't be so high in automatic freezing condition. So I directly picked out all the conditions where power numbers were above 1000w.

Routines (all recorded appliances in Home105)¶

Now all recorded appliances in Home105 are on the plots. By changing the date, I can tell the routine of appliance use day by day.

I randomly picked out three days: 2017-05-28, 2017-06-01, 2017-08-01 to see the timelines change in all recorded appliances.

What I want to find out are the followings:

  1. Did Home105 have a routine in using appliances in one day?
  2. Did the routine corresponding to typical appliances?

In Dec 2017, though the frequency of using microwave dropped, the tendency of using it gradually rose as Chritsmas approached. The frequency of using fridgefreezer also dropped but the tendency of using it didn't change a lot through the month. For the kettle use, the tendency didn't change so much but the frequency rose at the end of the month.

Compared to appliance in May, tendency of using microwave rose, frequency of using fridgefreezer dropped and frequency of kettle use was low but gradually kept up with that in May.

Part 3: Reflection and Hypotheses¶

Reflection¶

My reflection mainly focuses on some feedbacks on the process of dealing with data. I first thought the data was easy to analyze because in each csvfile there were only two rows. However, problems came gradually. First, I couldn't split the "time" into smaller items like year, month, day...so I needed to take them as an entirety. Then, I found that the time column was not continuous so I could not have a fixed x-axis. The biggest problem was to sort out the start points in each file. Two new tips I learned from here were: 1. add a new column and use 0/1 to label; 2. if it was really hard to delete the items, then just put them aside and use "reverse" to get the dataframe I want. These two tips really helped me come over the most difficult parts in analyzing all files. Finally, consistent data types and variable names always needs to be kept in mind. Sometimes, the bug was so small to figure out and usually it was the mistake of consistency. Programming needs patience and sometimes a little brain-twister. I suppose these feedbacks are not only useful for this time and can be applied to later programming.

Hypotheses¶

  1. Frequency of using appliances has a possitive correlation with the home user's age; Now I find such possitive correlation in microwave use, so I wonder if this condition can also be seen in other appliances. To test the hypotheses, I need more appliances data in SMILE Homes or personal information in IDEAL Homes from the data holder.

  2. Frequency of using appliances has a correlation with the home user's location, maybe also linking to the latitude of locations; I have found a correlation between microwave use and locations. The reason I mention the latitude of locations is because I can see a tendency in the chart above. Aberdeen is the northest location among three, and the top frequency of microwave use is also based there while Livingston is the southest among three, and people least frequently using microwave just lives there! To test the hypotheses, the same as in hypotheses 1, I need more appliances data or personal information. And specifically for this hypotheses, I also need to check the latitudes of each locations from Google.

  3. Each home has its own routine of using appliances in a day. From analyzing Home105, I find some small routines alike things only from 3 days. Perhaps when I go over through more dates and by dynamically showing the timelines in a day, I will finally get a fixed routine in each home.
